o":null,"image_credit_info":null,"data_clickthrough_info":null,"version_webp_callback":{}},"display_title":"Polaroid's new mobile printer turns your iPhone photos into stickers","choice":false,"mash_debut":false,"weed_in_america":false,"spotlight":false,"shortcode_data":{"gallery":[],"giftguide":{}},"excerpt":"That's not a rainbow-colored vape. It's a printer. ","show_sponsorship":null,"sponsorship_footer":null,"channel":"Tech","channel_label":"Tech","channel_link":"https://mashable.com/Tech/","tweet_text":"Polaroid's new mobile printer turns your iPhone photos into stickers"},{"_id":"5f45cd9601e6930053000008","id":"/article/iphone-12-pro-max-leak-lidar/","title":"iPhone 12 Pro Max leak appears to confirm rumored features including 120hz display, LiDAR auto-focus","title_tag":null,"author":"Amanda Yeo","post_date":"2020-08-26T02:48:53+00:00","post_date_rfc":"Wed, 26 Aug 2020 02:48:53 +0000","formatted_date":"08/26/2020","sort_key":"1KaOlG","link":"https://mashable.com/article/iphone-12-pro-max-leak-lidar/","content":{"plain":"Some rumored features of the upcoming iPhone 12 Pro Max have now been all but confirmed, thanks to Front Page Tech host and reliable leaker Jon Prosser â€” including a 120hz display refresh rate and LiDAR.\nTo be clear, the model Prosser showed off in his video on Tuesday is not technically the iPhone consumers will get in their hands. This one is from a product validation test batch, used for the last round of testing before the phone goes into mass production. Though it's unlikely, features could potentially still change or be removed. Still, this model is incredibly close to being finalized, and about as near as we can get right now to the iPhone that will be on shelves.\nFurther, this is only a look at the iPhone 12 Pro Max, so we don't know whether the iPhone 12 or iPhone 12 Pro will have the same features.\nSEE ALSO: Apple's iPhone 12 Pro will have a silky smooth ProMotion display, report claims\nFirst up, this sneak peek confirms that the iPhone 12 Pro Max will likely have LiDAR assisted auto-focus, which measures distance using lasers. The phone will let you record video in 4K at 120 FPS, as well as slow motion 4K at 240FPS for those stunning bee videos and Jackass-style shenanigans.\nProsser also noted the enhanced night mode (which offers extended exposure times when the phone is on a steady surface), advanced noise reduction, and bit depth video support. Further, while he was unable to test it himself, Prosser's source told him the iPhone 12 Pro Max's facial recognition for Face ID is faster, and will work from more angles.\nThe leak further indicates that the iPhone 12 Pro Max's display settings will allow a 120hz screen refresh rate, as well as an option for the phone to automatically switch to 60hz depending upon what's being shown on the screen. However Prosser noted not all test phones have a 120hz refresh rate as an option, making it a bigger question as to whether this feature will actually end up in the finalized model.\niPhone 12 Pro details:True Depth array same size. Bezels are â€œnoticeably thinnerâ€Slightly larger display - making the notch â€œappearâ€ smaller.Face ID works from wider angles. Even flat on a table.Sides are flat, but glass has slight curve.Rear cam module is 10% larger.â€” Jon Prosser (@jon_prosser) August 25, 2020\n\nProsser even shared some video of the iPhone 12 Pro Max, though not much is actually visible due to its phone case designed to prevent leaks. Fortunately, Prosser's source got a better look at the phone's design.\nAccording to the source, the iPhone 12 Pro Max's sides are flat, similar to the iPhone 5, but the edges of the display are slightly curved. The iPhone 12 Pro Max is also reportedly slightly lighter than the 11 Pro Max, despite the camera on the back being about 10 percent larger.\nNot everything could be hidden by the iPhone's anti-leak case either. Prosser also showed off a notable notch at the top of the screen, which appears a bit smaller than it is due to the phone's 6.7-inch screen and thinner bezels. However, it seems we'll have to wait a bit longer to see the iPhone 12's design for ourselves.\nRumours and speculation about the iPhone 12 have been swirling for a while now, with supply chain issues delaying launch beyond Apple's usual September reveal. Apple is currently expected to stagger the launch, releasing two 6.1-inch models first before following them with 5.4-inch and 6.7-inch models at a later date.\nWATCH: Our 5 favorite iOS 14 features, so far"},"image":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F118563%252F80e22a60-7c58-4a4c-99e8-f819f1b00f27.png%252F950x534__filters%253Aquality%252880%2529.png?signature=MNAG8wPQlgvu-Hqlngk9-B13_EA=&source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com","feature_image":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F118563%252F80e22a60-7c58-4a4c-99e8-f819f1b00f27.png%252F1438x0.png?signature=Ar9fcxM_kEuitXBSNgvp6BCuwbc=&source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com","responsive_images":[{"image":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F118563%252F80e22a60-7c58-4a4c-99e8-f819f1b00f27.png%252F280x158.png?signature=UmbZQBafMR-TOIdKNfc1ac9T8UM=&source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com","query":true,"size":"280x158#"},{"image":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F118563%252F80e22a60-7c58-4a4c-99e8-f819f1b00f27.png%252F560x316.png?signature=MD1NilkTCkfPtC9uGTcckvQ9h2I=&source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com","query":"(min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"560x316#"}],"responsive_images_html5":{"img_set_info":{"tag_attributes":{"alt":"iPhone 12 Pro Max leak appears to confirm rumored features including 120hz display, LiDAR auto-focus","src":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F118563%252F80e22a60-7c58-4a4c-99e8-f819f1b00f27.png%252F280x158.png?signature=UmbZQBafMR-TOIdKNfc1ac9T8UM=\u0026source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com","src_type":"png","loading":"lazy","version_webp_srcset":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F118563%252F80e22a60-7c58-4a4c-99e8-f819f1b00f27.webp%252F280x158.webp?signature=z6U63dbU1O5zIWWxhwuMGpZMR5g=\u0026source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com 280w","naturalWidth":"280","srcset":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F118563%252F80e22a60-7c58-4a4c-99e8-f819f1b00f27.png%252F280x158.png?signature=UmbZQBafMR-TOIdKNfc1ac9T8UM=\u0026source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com 280w","sizes":"280w"}},"image_caption_info":null,"image_credit_info":null,"data_clickthrough_info":null,"version_webp_callback":{}},"display_title":"iPhone 12 Pro Max leak appears to confirm rumored features including 120hz display, LiDAR auto-focus","choice":false,"mash_debut":false,"weed_in_america":false,"spotlight":false,"shortcode_data":{"ooyala":[{"data-slug":"eGlvwQQJok","data-source":"blueprint"}],"gallery":[],"giftguide":{}},"excerpt":"Looks like some of those rumors are are becoming reality.","show_sponsorship":null,"sponsorship_footer":null,"channel":"Tech","channel_label":"Tech","channel_link":"https://mashable.com/Tech/","tweet_text":"iPhone 12 Pro Max leak appears to confirm rumored features including 120hz display, LiDAR auto-focus"},{"_id":"5f48c73bbfff31006000008d","id":"/article/facebook-apple-tax/","title":"Facebook tries to warn users about Apple 'tax,' Apple says no","title_tag":null,"author":"Stan Schroeder","post_date":"2020-08-28T08:58:34+00:00","post_date_rfc":"Fri, 28 Aug 2020 08:58:34 +0000","formatted_date":"08/28/2020","sort_key":"1KbCw0","link":"https://mashable.com/article/facebook-apple-tax/","content":{"plain":"Apple and Facebook are clashing heads again.Â \nFacebook recently tried to inform its users that Apple is taking a 30 percent cut on Facebook's online events app, but Apple rejected the update, Reuters reported Friday.Â \nIn fact, Apple said no to Facebook twice.Â \nFirst, the social network asked Apple to waive its 30 percent fee, which it charges on in-app purchases, on Facebook's upcoming tool that would let users host paid online events. The idea behind the request was to offset losses incurred by the COVID-19 pandemic, so Facebook wanted to pass on all revenue to users, but Apple declined. Â \nThen, Facebook planned to launch the app with a notice saying that Apple has declined to waive its Apple Tax, as the 30 percent fee is sometimes called. However, Apple said no to that as well, citing an App Store rule that prohibits sharing \"irrelevant\" information with users.Â \n\"Donâ€™t include irrelevant information, including but not limited to information about Apple or the development process,\" Apple's App Store guidelines say.Â \nA few weeks ago, Facebook released an image showing what this notice would look like. The iOS variant (on the left) says \"Apple takes 30 percent of this purchase,\" while the notice on Android (right) says that \"Facebook doesn't take a fee from this purchase.\"Â \nNotably, according to Reuters, the Android version doesn't display the notice, either.Â \n\nFacebook isn't giving up, though.Â \n\"Now more than ever, we should have the option to help people understand where money they intend for small businesses actually goes. Unfortunately Apple rejected our transparency notice around their 30 percent tax but we are still working to make that information available inside the app experience,\" Facebook told Reuters.Â \nSEE ALSO: Microsoft backs Epic Games, says Apple is threatening game development\nEarlier this month, the two companies had another public clash, as Facebook was forced to launch its Gaming app on iOS without games. Apple's stance was that the app breaks an App Store rule about apps whose main purpose is distributing games (only Apple is allowed to have such an app). Facebook responded by mocking Apple in its Android app, and calling out the company for \"hurting players and developers.\"\nApple's App Store guidelines and rules have been under increased scrutiny in the past weeks, with Apple removing popular game Fortnite from the App Store for bypassing the 30 percent cut with in-game currency, and Fortnite's publisher Epic Games answering with a lawsuit.Â \n\"Apple's removal of Fortnite is yet another example of Apple flexing its enormous power in order to impose unreasonable restraints and unlawfully maintain its 100 percent monopoly over the iOS In-App Payment Processing Market,\" reads a legal complaint by Epic Games.Â "},"image":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fcard%252Fimage%252F1472018%252F25a27ca7-7333-42c3-8361-29684aadbef6.jpg%252F950x534__filters%253Aquality%252880%2529.jpg?signature=QnVqtBCMHYhV6S43CbPlnWIxnAY=&source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com","feature_image":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F118659%252F2586680c-e530-457b-ba49-0cdf3827748d.jpg%252F1438x0.jpg?signature=xuhJQvEUeB7rKAG61HgU3XLTDrU=&source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com","responsive_images":[{"image":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F118659%252F2586680c-e530-457b-ba49-0cdf3827748d.jpg%252F280x158.jpg?signature=sF1GogeI2arxJWt4rZAUq6Js-QM=&source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com","query":true,"size":"280x158#"},{"image":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F118659%252F2586680c-e530-457b-ba49-0cdf3827748d.jpg%252F560x316.jpg?signature=n6zNpKLo_Rt_0OH5ORyvoRDjuuY=&source=https%3A%2F%2Fblueprint-api-production.s3.amazonaws.com","query":"(min-resolution: 1.5dppx)","size":"560x316#"}],"responsive_images_html5":{"img_set_info":{"tag_attributes":{"alt":"Facebook tries to warn users about Apple 'tax,' Apple says no","src":"https://mondrian.mashable.com/uploads%252Fstory%252Fthumbnail%252F118659%252F2586680c-